PIL.Image.set_num_threads(multiprocessing.cpu_count())\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa80\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs42 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 4. Limit Frame Generation with Precise Sleep Timers\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading80\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 \cf0 If your Python script loops without any constraints, it will render frames as fast as your CPU can handle\'97sometimes pushing over 200 frames per second. Rendering ahead of time wastes a massive amount of electricity and generates unnecessary heat, since your live stream only requires 30 frames per second.\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\fs22 \AppleTypeServices \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f3\b\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 The Solution:
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  Add a precise clock timer inside your main rendering loop using Python's time module.\
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\fs22 \AppleTypeServices {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f3\b\fs32 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774 The Logic:
\f1\b0 \AppleTypeServices\AppleTypeServicesF2293774  Calculate how long it takes to render a single frame. If it finishes a frame in 5 milliseconds, tell the script to pause and sleep for the remaining 28 milliseconds before starting the next frame. This keeps your pipeline locked at an efficient 30 frames per second, keeping your hardware cool and stable.\
